Looking at the code, I can see exactly where the type mismatches are:

## Type Mismatch Locations

### Test File (lines 310, 326, 343, 344, 410)
In my test overrides, I'm passing `null` for optional string fields:

```typescript
// Line 310 - ❌ Type error
createMockEmail('msg1', 'thread1', 'test@example.com', {
  bodyPlain: 'Test plain text body',
  bodyHtml: null,  // ❌ Type 'null' not assignable to 'string | undefined'
});

// Line 326 - ❌ Type error  
createMockEmail('msg1', 'thread1', 'test@example.com', {
  bodyPlain: null,  // ❌ Type 'null' not assignable to 'string | undefined'
  bodyHtml: '<p>Test HTML body</p>',
});

// Lines 343-344 - ❌ Type errors
createMockEmail('msg1', 'thread1', 'test@example.com', {
  bodyPlain: null,  // ❌
  bodyHtml: null,   // ❌
});

// Line 410 (inside line 105) - ❌ Type error
createMockEmail('msg2', 'thread2', 'sender2@example.com', {
  bodyHtml: '<p>HTML body 2</p>',
  bodyPlain: null,  // ❌
});
```

The issue: `EmailMessage` interface defines these as `bodyPlain?: string` (optional), which means `string | undefined`, but NOT `null`.

### Implementation File (email-repository.ts lines 92, 93, 145)
Pre-existing issue with `headers` field:

```typescript
headers: email.payload.headers,  
// ❌ Type 'EmailHeader[]' not assignable to Prisma's 'InputJsonValue'
```

Prisma needs explicit casting for custom types → JSON.

Let me fix the test file issues:

